threat_severity.level_description: Severity HIGH because it was considered ransomware. Other contributing factors were that it has known exploits and it could not be run in sandboxes.

attributes.magic: ELF 64-bit LSB pie executable, x86-64, version 1 (SYSV), dynamically linked, interpreter /lib64/ld-linux-x86-64.so.2, BuildID[sha1]=9156d40709a913e9f6152845f311921dffff993a, for GNU/Linux 3.2.0, not stripped

crowdsourced_ai_results.analysis: The binary is a Linux variant of the Conti ransomware. It traverses directories to find and encrypt files using a hybrid encryption scheme (Salsa20 and RSA). It renames encrypted files with the `.conti` extension and drops a ransom note named `CONTI_README.txt`. The malware contains an embedded RSA public key for encrypting the file keys and a Tor C2 address (`http://contirec[.]poc[.]onion/-`). It also has functionality to terminate processes by iterating through `/proc` to prevent them from locking files.
